  "prompt": "Why astronauts have a white and an orange-coloured space suit?",
  "response": "Astronauts wear different colored space suits for specific purposes and missions. The most common colors you see are white and orange. Here\u2019s why:\n\n1. **White Space Suits:**\n   - **Extravehicular Activity (EVA):** White space suits are typically used during Extravehicular Activities, also known as spacewalks. The white color is highly reflective, which helps protect astronauts from the harsh solar radiation in space. It minimizes heat absorption and helps maintain a stable internal temperature.\n   - **Visibility:** White suits are highly visible against the dark background of space, making it easier for astronauts to see each other and for ground teams to monitor their movements.\n\n2. **Orange Space Suits:**\n   - **Launch and Entry:** Orange suits are usually worn during launch, reentry, and landing phases. These are known as Advanced Crew Escape Suits or Launch/Entry Suits. The bright orange color is chosen for its high visibility, especially in the case of an emergency or rescue situation. If an astronaut needs to be located quickly, the orange color stands out against various backgrounds like the ocean or terrain.\n   - **Safety and Rescue:** The suits are equipped with safety features and survival gear to protect astronauts in case of an emergency during these critical phases of the mission.\n\nEach color serves a specific function related to the safety and operational needs of the astronauts in different environments and stages of their missions.",
